<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1924-11-05T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1924-11-05T18:00:00-05:00" n="355" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d355">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/5707: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Mayer</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-11-05T18:00:00-05:00"><hi rend="italic">November 5,
                                        1924—6 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>269. Tokyo Embassy telegraphs November 5<note n="18" xml:id="d355fn18">Telegram not printed.</note> that Japanese Consul at Tsingtau
                            advises his Government our Consul there has agreed with Japanese and
                            British colleagues to advise Wu Pei-fu not to land in the event of his
                            arrival there.</p>
                        <pb facs="0504" n="390" xml:id="pg_390"/>
                        <p>Please advise Consul immediately that the Department could not approve
                            such intervention in Chinese internal affairs.</p>
                        <p>Repeat to Tokyo as Department’s No. 180.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>